title: Behind the Scenes: Androidify's AI-Powered Transformations with Firebase | Firebase After Hours #17
description:
Ever wondered how to turn yourself into an Android character using the power of AI? In this episode of Firebase After Hours we sat down with Rebecca from the Android team to get a behind-the-scenes look at the new Androidify app.

We explored how the team used Firebase AI Logic to transform selfies into custom Android bots. We dove deep into the tech stack, including:

* Firebase AI Logic for image analysis and description generation.
* Imagen and Nano Banana for creating stunning visuals.
* MLKit for on-device subject segmentation.
* Firebase Remote Config for dynamic updates and A/B testing.
* Firebase App Check to ensure the security of the app.

Whether you're a developer interested in AI, a Firebase enthusiast, or just curious about the magic behind Androidify, this video is a must-watch!

Chapters:
00:00 - Introduction
05:15 - Introducing Rebecca from the Android team
05:42 - Rebecca's journey with Firebase
11:08 - What is Androidify?
13:07 - How Firebase AI Logic powers Androidify
16:46 - Using Nano Banana for custom backgrounds
19:24 - Creating stickers with MLKit subject segmentation
20:25 - On-device vs. cloud processing
24:34 - The power of Firebase Remote Config
27:46 - Securing the app with Firebase App Check
33:16 - Q&A: Constraints and conditions for AI models
45:31 - Deep dive into Firebase App Check
56:49 - The team behind Androidify

In today‚Äôs episode, we have Ishant Sharma, one of India‚Äôs most experienced fast bowlers. From starting off in Delhi cricket clubs to becoming a key part of Team India for over a decade, Ishant has seen it all: the highs, the setbacks, and the lessons that shaped him both as a player and a person. This conversation captures his journey beyond just numbers on the scoreboard.

We talk about how he got into fast bowling, the challenges of breaking into the Indian team, and the dynamics inside the dressing room,  from Delhi vs Mumbai cricket culture to sledging battles with Australia. Ishant opens up about being banned for a test match, the differences he observed under Dhoni‚Äôs and Virat‚Äôs captaincy, and what makes bowlers like Bumrah so special. He also shares stories of over 30 runs conceded in a single over, the mental toll it took on him, and how he bounced back stronger.

In the last segment, Ishant reflects on young talent like Yashasvi Jaiswal, Shubman Gill, and Mayank Yadav, his proudest wickets, and the mental acceptance of moving on from Test cricket. He also talks about his rituals before bowling, his views on favouritism in selections, and how trolls and self-doubt shaped his mindset. A candid and honest look into the life of one of India‚Äôs most reliable pacers.

In today‚Äôs episode, we have Falguni Pathak, one of India‚Äôs most loved singers and the undisputed ‚ÄòGarba Queen.‚Äô From performing for just 25 rupees a show to creating iconic songs like ‚ÄúMaine Payal Hai Chhankai‚Äù and drawing crowds of over 60,000 people during Navratri, her journey has been nothing short of inspiring. In this conversation, she shares the highs, lows, and everything that shaped her into the artist people adore today.

We talk about her humble beginnings, the loss of her mother at a young age, her father‚Äôs resistance to her singing, and how her passion slowly turned into acceptance and support. She opens up about how Navratri became such a big part of her identity, the challenges of performing live, and why she believes folk music continues to hold such a deep connection with people. Along the way, she also shares her love for Lata Mangeshkar and Asha Bhosle, her dream collaborations, and the insecurities she still carries despite decades of success.

In the last segment, Falguni reflects on the changes she‚Äôs seen in three decades of Navratri, her rituals before and after shows, her dream of owning an aircraft and a yacht, and how she truly wants to be remembered. She also talks about the simplicity of folk songs, her relationship with the Gujarati diaspora abroad, and why she has never planned her life but instead embraced whatever came her way.

In today‚Äôs episode, we have Dr. Samir Dalwai, Director of New Horizons Child Development Centre and a leading developmental and behavioral pediatrician. With decades of expertise in child development, he has worked closely with parents and schools to guide healthier ways of raising children. In this conversation, he breaks down what effective parenting truly means in today‚Äôs world and how early experiences shape a child‚Äôs future.

We explore the importance of tone and balance in parenting, why hitting or strict discipline doesn‚Äôt work, and how children learn more from engagement and interaction than from easy comfort. Dr. Dalwai explains the difference between nurture and nature, why reading stimulates the brain far more than screen time, and how disappointment plays a role in building resilience. He also shares insights on autism, why its prevalence has risen so drastically, and how autistic children often have exceptional pattern recognition abilities.

In the last segment, we dive into the challenges of today‚Äôs tech-driven and socially isolated world, the dangers of excessive screen time, and why community and human interaction are more important than ever for children. Dr. Dalwai also answers questions around inclusivity in schools, whether autism can be prevented before birth, and what parents can do to raise children better equipped for the future.

title: These Facts about Nifty P/E ratio can help you invest better
description:
Feeling the market jitters? It's normal This video  explains why Indian equity market dips are routine and happen almost every year. Learn that the Nifty 50 has typically seen a correction of at least 10% annually, with an average dip of about 15%.

Discover why these drawdowns, though painful, are temporary, with prior highs usually reclaimed within 7-12 months, once the market finds its bottom. We'll reveal the dramatic impact of trying to time the market‚Äîmissing just a few of the best days can significantly reduce your returns, especially since many of these powerful recovery days often occur right after the worst downturns.

Understand how long-term investing in Indian equities has historically delivered double-digit annualized returns, with positive outcomes becoming far more consistent over longer horizons.

This video offers a clear framework for navigating market volatility: learn to budget for discomfort, ring-fence your near-term cash, and use market signals as guides, not hard switches. Volatility is simply the price of admission; time in the market is where the real compounding happens.

Watch to understand how to expect the dips, prepare for them, and stay invested through the discomfort to capture the powerful bursts that drive most of the returns in Indian equities.

#IndianStockMarket #Nifty50 #StockMarketCorrections #InvestingInIndia #MarketMindset #LongTermInvesting

In today‚Äôs episode, we have Dr. Abdulnasser Alshaali, the UAE‚Äôs Ambassador to India, who has played a key role in strengthening ties between the two nations. Prime Video India Presents
Two Much With Kajol And Twinkle Official Trailer
Starring Kajol, Twinkle Khanna, Salman Khan, Aamir Khan, Govinda, Chunky Panday, Vicky Kaushal, Kriti Sanon, Varun Dhawan, Alia Bhatt, Janhvi Kapoor, Karan Johar.
Created by Banijay Asia

Official Release Date September 25, 2025 on Prime Video India.

About:
Kajol and Twinkle are serving up a talk show with a twist - equal parts masti, magic and maybe even some manic energy. Expect wild hot takes, controversial opinions and the kind of honesty that makes you say, ‚ÄúDude, same!‚Äù 
Joining them are their friends who just happen to be some of the biggest stars in the country (and even the world). With eight unique pairs gracing the couch this season, the conversations jump from filmy nostalgia to family drama, love, paparazzi, fame and everything in between.
What sets it apart is the unapologetic female gaze - a perspective that‚Äôs funny, sharp, and not afraid to hold up a mirror to society. One moment you‚Äôre laughing embarrassingly loudly, the next you‚Äôre caught off guard by an insight that might make you question your own life choices. 
Basically, it‚Äôs a vibe: two women side-by-side, yapping with their friends. Think of it as the fun table at the party, sunny, chatty, and just unhinged enough to keep you hooked.

In today‚Äôs episode, we have Ruchir Sharma, bestselling author of 5 books, Chairman of Rockefeller International, and one of the world‚Äôs most respected investors and thinkers. He began writing for The Economic Times at just 17 and has since built a reputation for his sharp insights on politics, economics, and leadership. In this conversation, he opens up about his journey, his writing career, and the lessons from meeting global leaders including the time he met Vladimir Putin and was later asked to leave Russia.

We discuss the future of Indian politics, who could be the next Prime Minister, whether the opposition has a real chance, and how power is often misused in politics. Ruchir also shares his thoughts on world leaders like Putin and Trump, what emerging nations can learn from developed economies, and why the freebies culture may be holding India back. 

In the last segment, we dive into India‚Äôs growth story, from competition between states and infrastructure spending to unemployment, opportunities for young talent, and lessons we can take from China. Ruchir also explains what needs to change for India to rise as a true global power.

In today‚Äôs episode, we have Gaurav Gill, consultant psychologist and body language expert with Manobal Foundation, Delhi. With his expertise in reading human behaviour, he explains how much our gestures, expressions, and even the smallest body cues reveal about us. From spotting hidden emotions to decoding lies, his work bridges psychology and crime investigation in fascinating ways.

We discuss how professional criminals try to use specific gestures to appear innocent, how microexpressions can expose when someone is hiding the truth, and whether body language can help identify dangerous people, including pedophiles. Gaurav also breaks down the everyday mistakes we make, things as small as avoiding eye contact, crossing arms at the wrong moment, or mismatching words and actions that instantly create dislike and distrust in others. 

In the last segment, he shares the step-by-step process of detecting lies in high-stakes situations, the most difficult cases he‚Äôs had to decode, and what serial killers actually feel after their first crime. Gaurav explains the psychology of deception, the science behind spotting danger, and the subtle signals most people miss.

At times equities rally, in other phases debt performs better, and during uncertainty, gold or silver take the lead. The challenge? No single asset class works across all market cycles.

That‚Äôs where a multi-asset approach can help. By combining equity, debt, gold, and silver within one portfolio ‚Äî and adjusting allocations as markets change ‚Äî investors can aim for better diversification and potentially better risk-adjusted returns over the long term.

A more secure in-ear fit. IP57 dust, sweat, and water resistance. A clinical-grade Hearing Aid feature. Live Translation to communicate across languages. #AirPods #AirPodsPro #AirPodsPro3 #AppleEvent #Apple 

World‚Äôs best Active Noise Cancellation evaluation tested in July 2025 in accordance with IEC 60268-24 as compared with best-selling commercially available wireless in-ear headphones.

Built-in heart rate monitor is intended for use during workouts with the Fitness app and compatible third-party apps on iPhone running iOS 26 and later.

AirPods Pro 3 are dust, sweat, and water resistant for non-water sports and exercise.

The Hearing Aid feature has received FDA authorization. This feature is supported on AirPods Pro 2 and later with the latest firmware when paired with a compatible iPhone, iPad, or Mac with iOS 18, iPadOS 18, or macOS Sequoia and later, and is intended for people 18 years old or older with perceived mild to moderate hearing loss.

Live Translation works when paired with an Apple Intelligence‚Äìenabled iPhone running iOS 26 and later. Supports English (UK, U.S.), French (France), German, Portuguese (Brazil), and Spanish (Spain). For more information, see https://www.apple.com/ios/feature-availability/. 

Battery life depends on device settings, environment, usage, and many other factors.

title: Pehla Pyaar, Pehla Heartbreak üíî | Akshay Kumar, Aishwarya Rai Bachchan, Alia Bhatt, Ranbir Kapoor
description:
First love feels like discovering fire for the very first time. Everything burns brighter, every touch leaves an echo, every word feels sacred. You go to school just to see them smile in the hallway, and suddenly that smile is the most important sight in the world. You stay awake until sunrise because their voice feels better than sleep itself. Every song makes sense, every poem speaks your truth, every star in the sky seems less beautiful than they are. You‚Äôd choose them in this universe and in every universe that could ever exist. In their presence, time bends, pain disappears, and forever feels like something you can finally hold in your hands. You think this is it, the kind of love poets spent lifetimes chasing, the kind of love that could never be broken.
But then life happens. Distance grows where closeness once lived. Silence floods the places where laughter once echoed. The person who was once your entire world becomes a stranger you still dream about at night. The same memories that once made you smile now burn like open wounds that refuse to heal. You replay conversations in your head, wonder what you could have said, what you could have done differently. Maybe it wasn‚Äôt meant to be. Maybe the timing was cruel. Maybe the world was too heavy on two young hearts. And so, you‚Äôre left staring at your phone, almost typing their name, before remembering that they are no longer yours to reach.
The hardest part isn‚Äôt losing them. It‚Äôs learning how to exist without them. Waking up every day and remembering all over again that they are gone. Carrying a love that has nowhere to rest, like water slipping endlessly through your hands. Yet somehow, you keep breathing, you keep walking, you keep living with a heart that is shattered but still beating, broken but still full of hope. Because even after the fire fades, something inside you still aches to believe that beauty will return.
Sometimes, the love we cannot live without is the very love we must learn to survive without. ‚ù§‚Äç?

In today‚Äôs episode, we have Dr. Ashok Kumar Mittal, Member of Rajya Sabha and Founder & Chancellor of Lovely Professional University. From building one of India‚Äôs biggest private universities to stepping into politics, he shares how business and governance connect, what power really means, and the realities of navigating both worlds.

We discuss whether politicians are more powerful than businessmen, and how decisions are made in parliament, and why he chose politics as a way to drive change in education. Dr. Mittal also opens up about the business of education, the investments, challenges, and the criticism around universities focusing more on facilities than academics. He reflects on curriculum building, outdated policies, and the real reasons behind rising unemployment among graduates.

In the last segment, the conversation explores topics like the drug problem in Punjab, Bollywood‚Äôs influence, and whether even the most honest businessmen can be targeted by power. Dr. Mittal also shares personal stories about his family‚Äôs sweet shop, how he entered the automobile business, and the journey of starting LPU.

In our eighth episode of our special series with sensitive skin expert Cetaphil, we have Dr. Madhuri (M.D. Skin & V.D., D.D.V. Mumbai), an experienced dermatologist and cosmetologist who has worked extensively on skin health, treatments, and anti-aging solutions. She talks about India‚Äôs obsession with fairness, explains how dermatologists classify skin shades, and clears myths around tanning, marriage-related pressures, and what ‚Äúfairness‚Äù really means in medical terms.

We discuss treatments like skin lightening, peeling, micro-needling, and the rising popularity of Korean skincare. Dr. Madhuri shares the real differences between creams, serums, and oils, why certain marketing trends like rice water toners or coffee scrubs aren‚Äôt always effective, and how good skincare habits can directly boost self-esteem. She also talks about anti-aging, collagen products, sunscreen myths, and common mistakes people make at different ages.

Towards the end, she discusses trending ingredients like niacinamide and ceramides, how to layer actives safely, and the quick fixes celebrities often use. She also sheds light on future trends such as DNA-based skincare, regenerative medicine, and advanced treatments like mandelic acid.

In today‚Äôs episode, we have Gitanjali Babbar, the founder and director of Kat-Katha Foundation, an organisation dedicated to supporting women living and working in Delhi‚Äôs red-light areas. Gitanjali has spent years working on the ground, listening to the unheard voices of sex workers, and building initiatives to create real change in their lives. She reveals eye-opening truths we don‚Äôt see, but need to understand.

We discuss her experiences with the women trapped inside the red light areas, the brutal realities that women face, and the broken systems that trap them. From stories of violence and coercion to the myths society believes about consent and choice, Gitanjali explains how deeply rooted the problem is. 

In the last segment, she shares some of the most disturbing stories she has witnessed, the fear that keeps women from escaping, and how the cycle of exploitation continues generation after generation. She also opens up about what it will really take to bring change and the lessons her work at Kat-Katha has taught her.

In today‚Äôs episode, we have Suresh Sethi, Managing Director & CEO of Protean eGov Technologies Limited. With decades of experience in digital infrastructure and governance, he has played a key role in building systems like DigiLocker, Aadhaar services, and DigiYatra. In this conversation, he talks about how India is creating inclusive digital solutions that reach millions, and what makes our approach different from countries like the US and China.

We discuss the transformation of India Post, the role of digital identity, and how data privacy is being shaped by the new DPDP Act. Sethi explains how DigiLocker actually works, whether Aadhaar data is safe, and the systems that prevent fraud. The conversation also touches on digital elections, global comparisons, and how countries like Africa mirror India‚Äôs journey in adopting technology.

In the last segment, he talks about spotting entrepreneurial opportunities in developing economies, why local connection matters for any organisation, and which sectors still hold massive potential for digital disruption. It‚Äôs an inside look at how India is building trust, scale, and innovation for the future.

description:
The survival action series "Alice in Borderland" became the most watched Japanese Netflix title by worldwide audiences.

Now, the "games" that took the world by storm begin once again.

The uncharted journey led by the mysterious Joker card is about to unfold...

In today‚Äôs episode, we have Karan Aujla, singer, lyricist, and one of the most influential voices in Punjabi music. He opens up about the struggles behind fame, from losing his parents at a young age to facing extortion threats and violence in Canada. Despite success, he reflects on the void he still feels and the fears that continue to shape his life and music.

We dive into his emotional side, how he views love, marriage, and family, why he writes songs from a female perspective, and the stories behind some of his most popular tracks. Karan also talks about his insecurities, the pressure of constantly creating, and the balance between vulnerability and strength as a public figure. He also reveals his habit of reckless spending, the making of his new album, and the artists he draws inspiration from.

In the last segment, he shares how loneliness follows him despite success, how his wife anchors him, and why he still feels a constant need to protect his loved ones. He also opens up about what truly defines happiness for him today. This episode was delivered by Porter.
